<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Salix planifolia </i>is a deciduous, riparian shrub to 3 m tall. Its leaves are bicolored, highly glossy above, and glabrous to silky, hairy below with glands at the leaf bases. Plants produce abundant small seeds, which disperse in wind and water. Seeds remain viable for a week and germinate on moist, exposed mineral substrates. Plants will sprout from their root crown or stem base after fire or cutting (Uchytil 1991f). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Salix planifolia </i>is a widespread, high-elevation shrub, which ranges throughout much of the mountains of western North America. The alliance exists (Nature- Serve 2007a) in several western states, including Colorado, Montana, New Mexico, Utah, Washington, and Wyoming. <br/>
<br/>
Stands in the Rocky Mountains appear to vary significantly with regard to moisture regime and associated herbaceous species from those in California. Stands in California occupy streamsides on moderately sloping streams in the subalpine adjacent to many other upper-elevation riparian and meadow types. Saturated during the growing season, stand understories contain <i>Allium validum, Carex breweri, </i>and <i>C. scopulorum. </i>Ecologically, they share much similarity with the stands of the <i>Salix eastwoodiae </i>and <i>Salix orestera </i>alliances. While the National Vegetation Classification currently places associations with <i>S. planifolia </i> in the mixed shrub willow, <i>Salix boothii - Salix geyeriana - Salix lutea</i>, alliance; we are reserving judgement until more regional analysis is done for montane to high elevation riparian vegetation. </div>
</div>

	
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Observations</h4>
	<div class="text"> A few surveys document the alliance in the Sierra Nevada (M261E), including those from Harvey Monroe Hall, Mount Pleasant, and Snow Canyon RNAs (Cheng 2004), Yosemite National Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b), and elsewhere in the Sierra Nevada (Potter 2005). Taylor (1884) identified a <i>Salix planifolia-Carex scopulorum</i> association and Keeler-Wolf et al. (2003b) identified a provisional <i>Salix planifolia</i> association. However, these studies provide little information on species composition. We need further sampling and analysis to characterize the alliance in California. </div>
</div>

	

    
